[h1 
	" Key Items and Their Usage
	$LF
]h1
[ul 
	[li 
		" 
		[b 
			"Power Up!
		]b
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" Top speed of the car is slightly increased
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" Also improves acceleration
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" 
		[b 
			"Turbo
		]b
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" Similar to 
				[b 
					"Power Up!
				]b
				" but only temporarily increases top speed and acceleration
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" 
		[b 
			"Jump
		]b
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" Car is boosted into the air
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" Useful for skipping portions of the track
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" 
		[b 
			"Dynamite
		]b
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" Fires out the back of the vehicle and causes an explosion
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" Since 
				[b 
					"Raptor-Raptor
				]b
				" is driven backwards this can be used like 
				[b 
					"Jump 
				]b
				"to skip areas by running into the explosion
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
]ul
[ul 
	[li 
		" 
		[b 
			"Bomb
		]b
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				" 3 bombs/mines are placed statically at the location of the vehicle over a couple of seconds
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" When a car hits a bomb it is thrown into the air like 
				[b 
					"Dynamite
				]b
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" If the car is stationary all bombs are laid on top of themselves
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				" When hitting a stack of 
				[b 
					"Bomb
				]b
				"s their force is cumulative and thus throws the car further
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
]ul
[h4 id=AcquiringItemsAndManipulation 
	" Acquiring Items and Manipulation
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"In order to get items the play must first pick up 
	[b 
		"coins
	]b
	". These 
	[b 
		"coins
	]b
	" are used to "buy" a spin of the item wheel. Item wheels contain 8 items that are "randomly" selected. The wheel begins to spin and the player can then press a button to stop the wheel. A skilled player can accurately press a button to stop the wheel at the desired location.
	$LF
	[br 
	]br
	$LF
	"In actuality, these item wheels are not random. At any given time, one of three predetermined item wheels will be selected depending on the frame the 
	[b 
		"coin
	]b
	" in spent. Additionally, which set of three item wheels is available is dependent on the players position in the race (e.g. 2nd vs 6th) and the amount of laps (measured in half increments) the player has completed. More information, including a complete set of item heatmaps is available on my github here: 
	[a href=https://github.com/lazycurler/MotorToonGrandPrixResearch/tree/main/itemWheel rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"https://github.com/lazycurler/MotorToonGrandPrixResearch/tree/main/itemWheel
	]a
	$LF
]div
[h4 id=LapSkip 
	" Lap Skip
	$LF
]h4
[div class=p 
	"Arguably the most important time saving trick of this run is 
	[b 
		"Lap Skip
	]b
	". As the name implies, this is when a significant portion of the track is skipped such that when the player respawns the lap counter has incremented. The following is quick summary followed by a link to a more verbose explaination. The game tracks the players last physical location on the track which it uses when respawning the player. Separately, the game tracks the players progress along the track and, crucially, this will update even if the player isn't physically on the track (i.e. above it). Therefore, if the player can stay off the track for a significant portion (over 1/2) of a lap 
	[em 
		"and
	]em
	" cross over the track to update the players progress then a lap skip can occur. This happens when the players position updates over 1/2 of a lap in a single frame. A more in depth explanation with diagrams/examples can be found on my github here: 
	[a href=https://github.com/lazycurler/MotorToonGrandPrixResearch/tree/main/respawn rel=noopener external nofollow 
		"https://github.com/lazycurler/MotorToonGrandPrixResearch/tree/main/respawn
	]a
	$LF
]div
